'''[[Barbara Bergmann|Barbara Rose Bergmann]]''' (20 July 1927 – 5 April 2015)<ref name=Bio>{{Citation | contribution = Barbara Rose Bergmann (1927–) | editor1-first = James  | editor1-last = Cicarelli | editor2-first = Julianne  | editor2-last = Cicarelli| title = Distinguished women economists | pages = 26–30 | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Connecticut | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780313303319 }}</ref><ref name=Times>{{cite news | last = Schwartzapril | first = Nelson D. | title = Barbara Bergmann, trailblazer for study of gender in economics, is dead at 87 | work = [[The New York Times]] |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/12/business/barbara-bergmann-trailblazer-for-study-of-gender-in-economics-is-dead-at-87.html?_r=0 | publisher = [[The New York Times Company]] | location = New York | date = 11 April 2015 | accessdate = 12 April 2015 }}</ref> was an important [[Feminist economics|feminist economist]]. Her work covers many topics from [[childcare]] and gender issues to poverty and [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]].

