{{Infobox book | name = Imagine: How Creativity Works | image = Imagine - How Creativity Works (Jonah Lehrer book).jpg | caption = Hardcover edition | author = [[Jonah Lehrer]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Brain science]], [[creativity]] | genre = | publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin]] | pub_date = 2012 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 279 | isbn = 9780547386072 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Imagine: How Creativity Works''''' is the third non-fiction book by [[Jonah Lehrer]], published in 2012. It explores [[brain science]], and [[creativity]] and its social aspects.<ref name="Lengel2012">{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/ae/articles/2012/03/28/20120328republic-recommends-april-book-pick-jonah-lehre-imagine.html|title='Republic' April book pick: 'Imagine: How Creativity Works' |last=Lengel|first=Kerry |date=March 31, 2012 |publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]''|accessdate=7 April 2012}}</ref> By July 2012, the book had been recalled by its publisher due to factual inaccuracies.<ref name="Kellogg2012">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/features/books/jacketcopy/la-jc-jonah-lehrer-bob-dylan-20120730,0,7090461.story|title=Jonah Lehrer's Bob Dylan quotes lead to resignation | last=Kellogg| first=Carolyn|date=July 30, 2012|publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]''|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>
==Fabrication of quotations== In July 2012, Lehrer acknowledged that he fabricated some quotes attributed to [[Bob Dylan]].<ref name="WSJ20120730">Associated Press. [http://omg.yahoo.com/news/author-acknowledges-fake-dylan-quotes-resigns-181116844.html "Author acknowledges fake Dylan quotes, resigns"], ''omg Yahoo!'', July 30, 2012.</ref> Sale of the electronic book as well as physical shipment of the book has been halted.<ref name="WSJ20120730"/>
In an article on August 10, Steve Myers alleged that quotes from magician [[Teller (entertainer)|Teller]], of the performance duo [[Penn and Teller]], were fake, after a fan saw a discrepancy in previous quotes from Teller from an article in 2009 in [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'' magazine]], also by Lehrer.<ref name="Poynter">Myers, Steve. [http://www.poynter.org/latest-news/mediawire/184700/another-false-quotation-found-in-jonah-lehrers-imagine-penn-teller/ "Another false quotation found in Jonah Lehrer’s ‘Imagine’"], ''The Poynter Institute'', August 10, 2012.</ref> Teller confirmed that the quotes from the ''Wired'' article in 2009<ref name="Wired">Jonah Lehrer. [https://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/magazine/17-05/ff_neuroscienceofmagic?currentPage=all "Magic and the Brain: Teller Reveals the Neuroscience of Illusion"], ''Wired'' magazine, April 20, 2009.</ref> were accurate, while the ones from ''Imagine: How Creativity Works'' were not.
==See also== * ''[[How We Decide]]'' * ''[[Proust Was a Neuroscientist]]''
